jchrest.domainSpecifics

Class Scene

  • java.lang.Object
    • jchrest.domainSpecifics.Scene
  • Direct Known Subclasses:
    ChessBoard

    public class Scene
extends java.lang.Object
    Represents a 2D external environment that a CHREST model can "see" as a 2D ArrayList containing one SceneObject per coordinate. The ArrayList created has the following structure:
    • First-dimension elements represent columns (x-axis) in the external environment.
    • Second-dimension elements represent rows (y-axis) in the external environment.
    Constructing the data structure in this way means that coordinate specification must follow the form of x-coordinate then y-coordinate. Thus, coordinate specification in a Scene is congruent with the along the corridor, up the stairs approach to 2D grid reading.

    Rows and columns are zero-indexed and therefore, identifying coordinates in a Scene should not use coordinates specific to the external environment (unless coordinates for the external environment are also zero-indexed). However, Scenes are capable of returning the domain-specific coordinates of any coordinate they represent since the minimum x/y-coordinate that the Scene represents is required when #this#Scene(java.lang.String, int, int, int, int, jchrest.architecture.VisualSpatialField) is invoked.

             int height,
             int minDomainSpecificCol,

        Constructor. #this is initially "blind".
        Parameters:
        name - Human-readable identifier for #this.
        minDomainSpecificCol - The minimum column in the domain that #this is intended to represent. Note that this value must represent an absolute coordinate value in the domain.
        minDomainSpecificRow - The minimum row in the domain that #this is intended to represent. Note that this value must represent an absolute coordinate value in the domain.
        width - Represents the maximum number of indivisible columns that can be "seen".
        height - Represents the maximum number of indivisible rows that can be "seen".
        visualSpatialFieldRepresented - Set to null if #this does not represent a VisualSpatialField.

      • addObjectsToRow

        public void addObjectsToRow(int row,
                            java.util.ArrayList<SceneObject> objects)
        Adds the SceneObjects specified along the columns of the row specified from the minimum column in the row incrementally. If the number of SceneObjects specified is greater than the maximum number of columns in #this, the extra SceneObjects are ignored.

        If a coordinate already contains a jchrest.lib.SceneObject, it is overwritten.

      • computeErrorsOfCommission

        public int computeErrorsOfCommission(Scene sceneToCompareAgainst)
        Compute the errors of commission in this #this compared to another.
        Parameters:
        sceneToCompareAgainst -
        Returns:
        • If the number of squares in the #thiss to be used in the calculation are equal, the number of jchrest.lib.SceneObjects that are in this #this but not the other is returned. For example, if this #this were to have 4 SceneObjects and another Scene were to have 3, the output of this function would be 1 (blind and empty SceneObjects are not included in the calculation).
        • If the number of squares in #this that are to be used in the calculation are not equal, an error is thrown since a fair calculation can not be made in these circumstances.
        • If the number of jchrest.lib.SceneObjects in this #this is less than the number of jchrest.lib.SceneObjects in the #this compared against, 0 is returned.

      • computeErrorsOfOmission

        public int computeErrorsOfOmission(Scene sceneToCompareAgainst)
        Compute the errors of ommission in #this compared to the sceneToCompareAgainst specified.
        Parameters:
        sceneToCompareAgainst -
        Returns:
        • If the number of squares in the #thiss to be used in the calculation are equal, the number of jchrest.lib.SceneObjects that aren't in this #this but are in the other is returned. For example, if this #this were to have 3 jchrest.lib.SceneObjects and another Scene were to have 4, the output of this function would be 1 (blind and empty jchrest.lib.SceneObjects are not included in the calculation).
        • If the number of squares in the #thiss to be used in the calculation are not equal, an error is thrown since a fair calculation can not be made in these circumstances.
        • If the number of jchrest.lib.SceneObjects in this #this is greater than the number of jchrest.lib.SceneObjects in the #this compared against, 0 is returned.

        public float computePrecision(Scene sceneToCompareAgainst)
        Compute precision of this #this against the sceneToCompareAgainst specified, i.e. the percentage of non blind/empty SceneObjects in #this, that are placed on the same coordinates in both Scenes.

        To determine correct placement the result of invoking SceneObject.getObjectType() on each SceneObject in #this and the sceneToCompareAgainst are compared.

      • getItemsInScopeAsListPattern

        public ListPattern getItemsInScopeAsListPattern(int col,
                                                int row,
                                                int scope)
        Parameters:
        col -
        row -
        scope -
        Returns:
        All SceneObjects on coordinates +/- the specified scope from the coordinate specified by col and row from the most south-easterly coordinate to the most north-westerly coordinate (all columns in a row are processed before the next row is processed) as a ListPattern composed of ItemSquarePatterns (SceneObjects representing blind and empty coordinates are not included).

        The "item" for each ItemSquarePattern will be the result of invoking SceneObject.getObjectType() on each SceneObject present on the applicable coordinates.
